comments.text:
As Adnan mentioned, if jinns and angels aren't physically present (though he himself says they exist in our realm), then it's considered shirk. However, I don't quite understand why this would be the case. Even if jinns aren't physically visible, they still exist in our world and can communicate with us—so can we ask them for help? Or even if there isn’t communication, if I ask, for example, "Oh, Donald Trump, give me the power to destroy Pissrael" from my home, would that be shirk? In this case, Adnan seems to be in a dilemma. If he says yes, why? Because Trump is physically in the world and has the power to help, and if it’s shirk, then asking angels—whether they are physically present or not—would also be shirk. But if Adnan says no, then calling upon jinns or angels, even if they're not “physically present” (as in they are moujood but we don’t have communication just like Trump, he is in US and doesn’t know about my existence), should not be shirk either. 
The distinction between “physically present” or “not” seems confusing in Adnan's argument.
comments.author: @Meowmin-fo5jp

 Clarifying Istighātha, Du‘a, and the Misuse of "Shirk"

1. The Hukm (Islamic Ruling) on Istighātha (Seeking Help)

Istighātha (الاستغاثة) refers to seeking help or aid, whether from Allah or from His creation. Islamic scholars classify it into two types:

1. Permissible Istighātha (مشروعة) – Seeking help through means (asbāb) that Allah has created, without believing in independent power.

Example: Seeking help from a doctor, a living person, or even asking for the intercession (tawassul) of prophets and saints.

Evidence:

Qur’an – "فاستغاثه الذي من شيعته على الذي من عدوه"
(“So the one from his faction sought his help against the one from his enemy.”) (Surah Al-Qasas 28:15)

Here, the Quran itself uses "istighātha" for a human seeking help from another human (Prophet Musa عليه السلام).





2. Impermissible Istighātha (محرمة / شركية) – Seeking help from someone while believing they have independent divine power.

Example: Calling upon an entity believing it acts independently of Allah rather than as a means (wasīlah).

Evidence:

Qur’an – "إياك نعبد وإياك نستعين"
(“You alone we worship, and You alone we ask for help.”) (Surah Al-Fatiha 1:5)

Hadith – The Prophet ﷺ said:
"إذا سألت فاسأل الله، وإذا استعنت فاستعن بالله"
(“If you ask, ask Allah; if you seek help, seek help from Allah.”) (Jami‘ at-Tirmidhi 2516, Hasan)





2. The Classification of Shirk Is Not in Traditional Sunni Islam

Classical Sunni theology (Ash‘ari and Maturidi) does not classify shirk into rigid categories like "major" and "minor." This threefold classification of Tawhid (Rububiyyah, Uluhiyyah, Asma’ wa Sifat) and shirk (major/minor) was developed later by Ibn Taymiyyah and Muhammad ibn Abd al-Wahhab.

Traditional scholars focused on the essence of Tawhid:

Belief in Allah’s absolute oneness and that all power ultimately belongs to Him.

Rejecting polytheism (shirk) as the attribution of divine power to others besides Allah.



3. The Meaning of Du‘a and How It Is Misused in Shirk Accusations

Du‘a (دعاء) means:

A simple call (nidā’).

A request (talab).

Worship (‘ibādah) if directed to someone with belief in their divine power.


Not every du‘a is worship.

Evidence from the Qur’an:

"لا تجعلوا دعاء الرسول بينكم كدعاء بعضكم بعضا"
(“Do not make the calling of the Messenger among you like the calling of one another.”) (Surah An-Nur 24:63)

This verse proves that du‘a does not always mean worship because people "call" each other in everyday life.



Misuse of the term "shirk" by certain groups:

Some Salafi interpretations generalize du‘a as worship in all cases.

This leads to accusing legitimate Sunni practices (such as tawassul and istighātha) of shirk unfairly.



4. Calling Jesus (‘Isa عليه السلام) as a Muslim – Istighātha or Worship?

If a Muslim calls upon Jesus (‘Isa) without believing he is God, it remains a linguistic act (nidā’) and not shirk.

However, due to historical theological sensitivities, such an action can be misleading and should be avoided.

The real issue is intention: If a person believes Jesus has independent divine power, then it becomes shirk.


5. Conclusion

Istighātha is permissible if done through lawful means (asbāb), like asking for du‘a or intercession.

Calling upon a prophet or saint is not automatically shirk unless one believes they have divine power.

The later categorization of shirk is not from classical Sunni theology.

Du‘a has multiple meanings and should not be misused to accuse others of shirk.

I posted this x as well 

Brother Daniel,

I watched the 7 hours, 53 minutes and 38 seconds discussion between you and Adnan. You both have been among my favorite speakers on YouTube when it comes to defending Islam. But Brother Daniel, you have lost my respect. You are not upholding the principle of loving for the sake of Allah and hating for the sake of Allah—instead, you are following your own desires. Yes, we are all human, and we all make mistakes, but persisting in wrongdoing knowingly is dangerous. We should never want to be wrongdoers, but even worse is defending what is clearly wrong.

Please read this in its entirety. This is only my second post on X in my entire life, and I am saying this with sincerity.

I want to share something with you from my own experience. For years, whenever I came across the topic of Tawheed in Aqeedah, I would think, “I’m already Muslim, why do I need to study this?” So, I would skip it. And I’ve seen so many people do the same—when given a simple book on Tawheed, they brush it off like it’s only for non-Muslims. That mindset is dangerous.

When Brother Adan told you that you have an issue in Aqeedah, he wasn’t calling you a deviant or a kafir. He was simply telling you: “Brother, go back, read, and understand.” The Prophet ﷺ said:

	“When Allah wills good for someone, He grants him understanding in the religion.” (Bukhari & Muslim)

So, when someone points out a flaw in your Aqeedah, see it as a wake-up call, not an attack.

But honestly, my respect for you dropped when I saw you defending someone who says Imams are better than Prophets. How can you even open your mouth on this? If I heard someone say that, I wouldn’t even hesitate to call it a statement of kufr. Allah says in the Qur’an:

	“And [mention] when We took from the prophets their covenant, including you [O Muhammad], and from Noah and Abraham and Moses and Jesus, the son of Mary; and We took from them a solemn covenant.” (Surah Al-Ahzab 33:7)

Prophethood is a divine selection—nobody, no scholar, no Imam, no leader can ever be higher than a Prophet. The Prophet ﷺ said:

	“The best of mankind are my generation, then those who come after them, then those who come after them.” (Bukhari & Muslim)

Even the Sahabah, the best of the Ummah, never claimed to be higher than the Prophets. So how can someone today even think of saying this?

Brother, as far as I’m concerned, what you’ve done is worse than Yasir Qadhi’s mistakes. I’m telling you straight: Repent and retract this defense of falsehood. I spent my entire weekend listening to your arguments, every single line. And I saw how you kept trying to defend it with your own reasoning. But Brother Adnan completely broke down your arguments using Usul al-Din (Fundamentals of Religion).

Listen carefully: There is NO room for ijtihad (personal reasoning) in Aqeedah. In matters like Tawheed, Prophethood, and the fundamentals of faith, our job is to submit to what Allah and His Messenger ﷺ have taught—no opinions, no debates, no “but I think…” Just submission.

And one last thing: Remove this poison from your heart against people who correct you. Yes, some Muslims might be harsh in their tone, but if they are upon correct Aqeedah, don’t let your ego block you from seeing the truth. Right now, you have two problems—one in Aqeedah and one in attitude. Fix both before it’s too late.

Final Advice to You:

Reflect on your words, because you will stand before Allah on the Day of Judgment. If you have spoken falsely about His religion, what excuse will you give? What defense will you have when the Prophet ﷺ himself is a witness against you?

Allah warns us:

	“And do not say about Allah that which you do not know.” (Surah Al-A’raf 7:33)

You still have time to correct this. Repent, retract, and humble yourself before the truth. Because in the end, your arguments won’t matter only what Allah accepts will.

May Allah guide us all.

The hadith of Uthman bin Hunaif is indeed authentic, where a blind man sought the Prophet ﷺ’s intercession during his lifetime, and the Prophet ﷺ instructed him to make du’a and use his supplication as a means of healing. However, it’s crucial to note that the Prophet ﷺ was alive at that time, and this action was specific to his lifetime.

After the Prophet ﷺ’s death, there is no evidence that any of the Sahabah (companions) ever made du’a to the Prophet ﷺ or sought his intercession in the same way. The correct understanding in Islam is that after the death of the Prophet ﷺ, we cannot make du’a to him or anyone else.

Allah says in the Qur’an:

	“And when they wronged themselves, they came to you [O Muhammad] and asked forgiveness of Allah, and the Messenger asked forgiveness for them…” (Surah Al-Nisa 4:64)

This verse shows that the intercession of the Prophet ﷺ was permissible while he was alive, but after his death, we rely on Allah alone for forgiveness and supplication. In the hadith, it’s clear that no companion made du’a to the Prophet ﷺ after his death, showing the importance of direct supplication to Allah.

As for seeking intercession, the correct path is asking Allah directly, as the Prophet ﷺ taught:

	“If you ask, ask of Allah; and if you seek help, seek help of Allah.” (Sunan al-Tirmidhi)

May Allah guide us all to follow the Sunnah in its correct context.
